## How to Use This .gitignore

1. Place this file in the root of the repository:
   ```bash
   cp .gitignore /path/to/fedora-43-upgrade-docs/.gitignore
   ```

2. Verify it's working:
   ```bash
   git check-ignore -v <filename>
   ```

3. Force add exceptions:
   ```bash
   git add -f important-file.txt
   ```

4. Check what will be ignored:
   ```bash
   git status -u
   ```

## Important Notes

- The main documentation files (README.md, CHANGELOG.md, etc.) are explicitly included with `!` patterns
- All backup and system files are ignored (users shouldn't commit personal backups)
- Build artifacts and compiled files are ignored
- Sensitive information is ignored (credentials, API keys, private keys)
- IDE/editor files are ignored for cross-platform compatibility

## Customizing for Your Project

If you add new file types to track, remember to:
1. Update this .gitignore to ignore similar temporary files
2. Use `!important-file.ext` to force include if needed
3. Document any special cases in comments

## Troubleshooting

If a file is still being tracked despite .gitignore:
```bash
git rm --cached filename.txt
git commit -m "Remove filename.txt from tracking"
```

If you want to ignore a previously tracked file:
```bash
git rm --cached --force filename.txt
git add .gitignore
git commit -m "Add filename.txt to .gitignore"
```

## Testing the .gitignore

```bash
# See what will be ignored
git check-ignore -v *

# Verify all files are properly categorized
git status

# Before committing to repo
git status --short
```

